'''Koyasu Shrine''' (子安神社) is a shrine located in {{ill|Hachiōji|ja|八王子市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tokyo Metropolis|ja|東京都|12=draft}}, in Myojin-cho. It is considered the oldest shrine in Hachiōji.<ref>[https://koyasujinja.or.jp/ Koyasu Shrine] - Official Website</ref>

== Overview ==

The shrine is located about a one-minute walk northwest of {{ill|Keiō-Hachiōji Station|ja|京王八王子駅|12=draft}}.

According to the ''{{ill|Shinpen Musashi Fudoki Kō|ja|新編武蔵風土記稿|12=draft}}'', the shrine was founded in {{ill|759|ja|759th year|12=draft}} ({{ill|Tenpyō-Hōji|ja|天平宝字|12=draft}} 3) by a man named Tachibana Ukyo-no-Shōyu (橘右京少輔) to pray for the safe childbirth of the empress of the reigning emperor, {{ill|Emperor Junnin|ja|淳仁天皇|12=draft}}.<ref name="jinjacho"/><ref name="yuisho">[https://koyasujinja.or.jp/yuisyo.html History] - Koyasu Shrine</ref>{{sfn|Shinpen Musashi Fudoki Kō Koyasu Village}}. Because of this history, Koyasu Shrine has been revered as a place of prayer for safe childbirth up to the present day.

The shrine has also historically received devotion from warriors. It is said that {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshiie|ja|源義家|12=draft}}, during his campaign against the Ōshū region, planted a keyaki ({{ill|Zelkova serrata|ja|ケヤキ|12=draft}}) tree in the shape of a ship as a votive offering, and this is said to be the origin of the nearby place name "Funamori" (船森).<ref name="yuisho"/>

During the early modern period, starting with {{ill|Tokugawa Iemitsu|ja|徳川家光|12=draft}}, successive shoguns granted the shrine {{ill|Shuin|ja|朱印|12=draft}}, a mark of official recognition. Because of this connection, the shrine's crest is the same as that of the Tokugawa family, the {{ill|Aoi-mon|ja|葵紋|12=draft}}.<ref name="yuisho"/>

In {{ill|1872|ja|1872nd year|12=draft}} (Meiji 5), the shrine was Ranked as a ''mura-sha'' (village shrine), and in {{ill|1943|ja|1943rd year|12=draft}} (Shōwa 18), it was elevated to the status of ''gōsha'' (district shrine).<ref name="yuisho"/>

The shrine was completely destroyed twice, first in the {{ill|Great Fire of Hachiōji|ja|八王子大火|12=draft}} on April 22, {{ill|1897|ja|1897th year|12=draft}} (Meiji 30), and again in the {{ill|Hachiōji Air Raid|ja|八王子空襲|12=draft}} on August 2, {{ill|1945|ja|1945th year|12=draft}} during {{ill|World War II|ja|第二次世界大戦|12=draft}}.<ref name="yuisho"/>

