'''Koyasu Shrine''' (子安神社) is a shrine located in [[:en:Hachiōji|Hachiōji]], [[:en:Tokyo|Tokyo Metropolis]], in Myojin-cho. It is considered the oldest shrine in Hachiōji.<ref>[https://koyasujinja.or.jp/ Koyasu Shrine] - Official Website</ref>
== Overview ==
The shrine is located about a one-minute walk northwest of [[:en:Keiō-hachiōji Station|Keiō-Hachiōji Station]].
According to the ''{{ill|Shinpen Musashi Fudoki Kō|ja|新編武蔵風土記稿|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinpen Musashi Fudoki Kō|qq=}}'', the shrine was founded in [[:en:759|759]] ([[:en:Tenpyō-hōji|Tenpyō-hōji]] 3) by a man named Tachibana Ukyo-no-Shōyu (橘右京少輔) to pray for the safe childbirth of the empress of the reigning emperor, [[:en:Emperor Junnin|Emperor Junnin]].<ref name="jinjacho"/><ref name="yuisho">[https://koyasujinja.or.jp/yuisyo.html History] - Koyasu Shrine</ref>{{sfn|Shinpen Musashi Fudoki Kō Koyasu Village}}. Because of this history, Koyasu Shrine has been revered as a place of prayer for safe childbirth up to the present day.
The shrine has also historically received devotion from warriors. It is said that [[:en:Minamoto no Yoshiie|Minamoto no Yoshiie]], during his campaign against the Ōshū region, planted a keyaki ([[:en:Zelkova serrata|Zelkova serrata]]) tree in the shape of a ship as a votive offering, and this is said to be the origin of the nearby place name "Funamori" (船森).<ref name="yuisho"/>
During the early modern period, starting with [[:en:Tokugawa Iemitsu|Tokugawa Iemitsu]], successive shoguns granted the shrine {{ill|Shuin|ja|朱印|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shuin|qq=}}, a mark of official recognition. Because of this connection, the shrine's crest is the same as that of the Tokugawa family, the {{ill|Aoi-mon|ja|葵紋|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aoi-mon|qq=}}.<ref name="yuisho"/>
In [[:en:1872|1872]] (Meiji 5), the shrine was Ranked as a ''mura-sha'' (village shrine), and in [[:en:1943|1943]] (Shōwa 18), it was elevated to the status of ''gōsha'' (district shrine).<ref name="yuisho"/>
The shrine was completely destroyed twice, first in the {{ill|Great Fire of Hachiōji|ja|八王子大火|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Great Fire of Hachiōji|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} on April 22, [[:en:1897|1897]] (Meiji 30), and again in the {{ill|Hachiōji Air Raid|ja|八王子空襲|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachiōji Air Raid|qq=}} on August 2, [[:en:1945|1945]] during [[:en:World War II|World War II]].<ref name="yuisho"/>
